│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.     │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an assertion failure   │
│ in BoUpSLP::ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps():                    │
│ \"hasValidDependencies() && 'increment of unscheduled deps would be      │
│ meaningless'\". This indicates that we are attempting to increment or    │
│ decrement the unscheduled dependency counter on a ScheduleData whose     │
│ dependencies have not been initialized (Dependencies == InvalidDeps).    │
│ Assertions in LLVM are designed to catch earlier logic errors;           │
│ therefore, we must ensure we never call incrementUnscheduledDeps unless  │
│ hasValidDependencies() is true.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug    │
│ log shows the SLP scheduler processing bundles and decrementing          │
│ dependencies for both def-use, memory, and control dependencies. The     │
│ crash occurs during handling of control/memory dependencies:\n- \"check  │
│ for readiness (mem): %call\"\n- \"check for readiness (ctrl):            │
│ %call\"\nRight after that, the assertion fires in                        │
│ incrementUnscheduledDeps. In the scheduler, DecrUnsched() is used to     │
│ decrement unscheduled deps for various dependency types, and it          │
│ currently allows decrementing for control dependencies even when         │
│ hasValidDependencies() is false.\n\nSpecifically, DecrUnsched            │
│ contains:\n  if ((IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies()) &&\n        │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) { ... }\nThis means when        │
│ IsControl is true, incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) is invoked even if       │
│ hasValidDependencies() is false, which directly violates the assertion   │
│ inside incrementUnscheduledDeps.\n\nThe logs before the crash also show  │
│ several \"reset schedule because ... was already scheduled\" and complex │
│ rescheduling of bundles, with copyable elements and reused scalars.      │
│ However, the immediate cause is the unconditional decrement for control  │
│ deps.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe scheduler attempts to treat        │
│ control dependencies specially by decrementing their counters even if    │
│ dependency info hasn’t been initialized (hasValidDependencies() ==       │
│ false). But incrementUnscheduledDeps asserts that hasValidDependencies() │
│ must be true. The mismatch between the DecrUnsched guard and the         │
│ assertion is the direct cause of the crash.\n\nIn normal flow,           │
│ dependencies are initialized via calculateDependencies() before          │
│ scheduling. However, control dependencies may point to ScheduleData      │
│ entities whose direct deps were cleared (clearDirectDependencies()),     │
│ leaving Dependencies/UnscheduledDeps == InvalidDeps. Calling             │
│ incrementUnscheduledDeps() on such data is invalid.\n\nTherefore, the    │
│ root bug is the condition in DecrUnsched allowing                        │
│ incrementUnscheduledDeps on control deps without verifying               │
│ hasValidDependencies().\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n- Location: In          │
│ BlockScheduling::schedule(), inside DecrUnsched lambda near lines        │
│ ~5410.\n- Change the condition to only call incrementUnscheduledDeps     │
│ when hasValidDependencies() is true, regardless of IsControl. This       │
│ aligns with the assertion contract and prevents attempts to modify       │
│ counters in an uninitialized state.\n\nEdit:\nLines 5410-5416:\nFrom:\n  │
│ if ((IsControl || Data->hasValidDependencies()) &&\n                     │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) {\n    ...\n  }\nTo:\n  if      │
│ (Data->hasValidDependencies() &&\n                                       │
│ Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1) == 0) {\n    ...\n  }\n\nThis         │
│ prevents calling incrementUnscheduledDeps on control dependencies unless │
│ their dependency info is valid. If dependencies are not yet valid, we    │
│ skip decrementing here; they will be processed when deps are             │
│ computed/validated.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy tightening the guard in        │
│ DecrUnsched to require hasValidDependencies(), we avoid violating the    │
│ invariant enforced by incrementUnscheduledDeps. This fixes the immediate │
│ crash without altering broader scheduling semantics. Control             │
│ dependencies will be handled once their dependency data is available,    │
│ preserving correctness and stability of the scheduler."})                │
